ymvg.camera_model.CameraModel.project_camera_frame_to_3d", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "self", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "pts3d", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": ["take 3D coordinates in camera frame and convert to world frame"]}, {"name": "pymvg.camera_model.CameraModel.project_3d_to_camera_frame", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "self", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "pts3d", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": ["take 3D coordinates in world frame and convert to camera frame"]}, {"name": "pymvg.camera_model.CameraModel.camcenter_like", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "self", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "nparr", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": ["create numpy array of camcenters like another array", "--------------------------------------------", "misc. helpers"]}], "class_variables": [{"name": "pymvg.camera_model.CameraModel.__slots__", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pymvg.camera_model.CameraModel.AXIS_FORWARD", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pymvg.camera_model.CameraModel.AXIS_UP", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pymvg.camera_model.CameraModel.AXIS_RIGHT", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pymvg.camera_model.CameraModel.Q", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pymvg.camera_model.CameraModel.Qt", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pymvg.camera_model.CameraModel.M", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pymvg.camera_model.CameraModel.translation", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pymvg.camera_model.CameraModel.Q_inv", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pymvg.camera_model.CameraModel.t_inv", "type": null, "documentation": []}], "instance_variables": [], "inner_classes": [], "documentation": ["an implementation of the Camera Model used by ROS and OpenCV\n\nTranformations: We can think about the overall projection to 2D in\ntwo steps. Step 1 takes 3D world coordinates and, with a simple\nmatrix multiplication and perspective division, projects them to\nundistorted 2D coordinates. Step 2 takes these undistorted 2D\ncoordinates and distorts them so they are 'distorted' and match up\nwith a real camera with radial distortion, for example.\n\n3D world --(step1)----> undistorted 2D ---(step2)----> distorted 2D\n\nStep 1 is accomplished by making the world coordinates a\nhomogeneous vector of length 4, multiplying by a 3x4 matrix M\n(built from P, R and t) to get values [r,s,t] in which the\nundistorted 2D coordinates are [r/t, s/t]. (The implementation is\nvectorized so that in fact many points at once can be\ntransformed.)\n\nStep 2 is somewhat complicated in that it allows a separate focal\nlength and camera center to be used for distortion. Undistorted 2D\ncoordinates are transformed first to uncorrected normalized image\ncoordinates using parameters from P, then corrected using a\nrectification matrix. These corrected normalized image coordinates\nare then used in conjunction with the distortion model to create\ndistorted normalized pixels which are finally transformed to\ndistorted image pixels by K.\n\nCoordinate system: the camera is looking at +Z, with +X rightward\nand +Y down. For more information, see\nhttp://www.ros.org/wiki/image_pipeline/CameraInfo\n\nAs noted on the link above, this differs from the coordinate\nsystem of Harley and Zisserman, which has Z forward, Y up, and X\nto the left (looking towards +Z).'"]}], "exports": []}]}